Title: Monel slime table
Name: Sturtevant, J. Bevier (Joseph Bevier), 1851-1910
Abstract: Caption added to print and signed October 26th, 1956: "This is a picture of a Monel Slime Table, which was invented by Ira Monel, an old time mill operator in Boulder County, about the year 1906. It is a slime table about 6 feet in width and twelve to 16 feet in length. The fine materials, minus 100 mesh, were fed to the table on a thin stream, a good portion of the minerals adhering to the canvas as it moved along slowly. Toward the end of the belt these were washed with clear water to remove any adhering sands, and then a spray washed them into a box where they were collected as finished material. The table was originally designed for tungsten ores but was used in the gold mills as well." Another caption: "Now 195seven Pres. 1st National Bank, Boulder, Colorado  was Manager Wolf Tongue Mining Co., Nederland, Colorado, 1904-1952."
Subject Geographic: Boulder (Boulder, Colorado, United States, North America) (populated place)
